<HEADLINE>
<P>
PLATFORM; WHY BACK REFORM? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NICHOLAS V. SEIDITA of Northridge comments on why those with adequate health 
care should be concerned about reform. The following is adapted from his 
remarks at the Sepulveda Unitarian Universalist Society. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 What does creating a national health system have to do with me? 
</P>
<P>
 Because I'm frightened of what our market system health care may do to deny 
needed care to my children and grandchildren.Because of what long-term illness 
could do to impoverish my wife and myself, as it did to my two widowed aunts. 
</P>
<P>
 Because, today, my loved ones can be denied treatment at emergency facilitiies 
that have been closed or packed by the emergencies of children, women and men 
who can't afford more economical preventive primary care.  
</P>
<P>
 Because of what marketing health care is doing to 37 million Americans without 
insurance. 
</P>
<P>
 Because I fear the reappearance of tuberculosis and other once-conquered 
diseases. 
</P>
<P>
 Because of what soaring health costs are doing to undermine American business 
in an interdependent world market. 
</P>
<P>
 Finally, I fear what the growing health crisis and its denial are doing to our 
economy, our democracy and to our people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
