<HEADLINE>
<P>
GOLF ROUNDUP; PRICE STILL THE HOTTEST DESPITE DALY'S RALLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 John Daly, playing his first PGA tournament since his November suspension, 
made a startling run in the Honda Classic on Sunday at Ft. Lauderdale, Fla., 
before finishing four strokes behind golf's hottest player -- Nick Price. 
</P>
<P>
 Price shot a five-under-par 66 to win by one stroke. It was his seventh 
international victory in less than 12 months. Price's 276 total, eight-under, 
left Craig Parry one back. Parry had a closing 67. 
</P>
<P>
 Despite his great play, Price doesn't consider himself the best in the world 
yet. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm probably in the top three or four," he said. "But to be No. 1 in the 
world, well, you have to have some majors in there." 
</P>
<P>
 Daly, the PGA's longest hitter and one of the game's big draws, closed within 
two strokes of the lead with a three-under 68 and finished in a fourth-place 
tie. 
</P>
<P>
 "If I had a hat on, I'd take my hat off to myself," Daly said. 
</P>
<P>
 Brandel Chamblee, who led or shared the lead through the first three rounds, 
birdied the last hole to match par 71 and was third -- his career-best finish 
-- at 278. 
</P>
<P>
 Daly was tied at 280 with Masters champion Bernhard Langer of Germany, Davis 
Love III and Curtis Strange. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Jim Albus shot a one-over-par 73, but maintained his wire-to-wire lead and won 
the Vantage at The Dominion PGA Seniors tournament at San Antonio. 
</P>
<P>
 Albus finished at eight-under-par 208 to win his third Senior Tour event, his 
first since the 1993 GTE Suncoast Classic. 
</P>
<P>
 He finished one shot ahead of two-time tournament champion Lee Trevino, Graham 
Marsh of Australia and George Archer. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Donna Andrews, who carried a three-shot lead into the final round of the 
Ping-Welch's Championship, survived a one-over-par 73 at Tucson, finishing at 
12-under 276 to defeat Judy Dickinson and 1992 champion Brandie Burton by three 
shots. 
</P>
<P>
 Dickinson carded a 68 -- a spectacular performance amid the problems created 
by 25- to 35-m.p.h. gusts -- but couldn't make up an eight-shot deficit. 
</P>
