<HEADLINE>
<P>
100 PEOPLE INVOLVED IN DRUNKEN MELEE IN MALIBU 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By J. E. MITCHELL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A drunken melee involving more than 100 people broke out in front of a popular 
Malibu roadside eatery Sunday afternoon, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 More than 16 deputies from the Ventura County Sheriff's Department and at 
least one California Highway Patrol unit converged on a section of beach in 
front of Neptune's Net restaurant, 42505 Pacific Coast Highway, about 4 p.m. to 
quell a drunken party that had apparently grown out of control, according to 
Sheriff's Lt. Michael Gullon. 
</P>
<P>
 Gullon said one man was arrested for failing to disperse during the melee, 
which took the officers -- along with a Ventura County sheriff's helicopter 
unit -- more than 90 minutes to control. 
</P>
<P>
 "We believe there were several beer kegs involved. It was a situation where 
people just had way too much to drink," Gullon said. "When we got on scene, it 
was out of control." 
</P>
<P>
 The name of the arrested man was not immediately available. 
</P>
<P>
 What sparked the melee was not clear Sunday night, but Gullon said arriving 
deputies saw a fight going in an impromptu boxing ring that had been set up on 
the beach and several other fights nearby. J. E. MITCHELL 
</P>
</TEXT>
