<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: CYPRESS; DISTRICT PLANS POLICY ON SEX HARASSMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIMI KO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Cypress School District next month plans to adopt a policy that would 
allow expulsion of any student who sexually harasses another student or 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
 Under the policy, students may face expulsion for making graphic sexual 
comments about other students, telling sexual jokes or stories, touching 
classmates or their clothes in a sexual manner, spreading sexual rumors, 
displaying sexually suggestive objects or retaliating against students who 
report policy violators. 
</P>
<P>
 Unwelcome sexual flirtations or propositions also would be prohibited. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition, if a sexual relationship between a student and a teacher or other 
district employee is reported, the district would conduct an investigation. 
Should such a relationship be found to exist, the student may face expulsion, 
while the employee may face termination. 
</P>
<P>
 District officials said they will consider the policy to provide "a learning 
environment that is free of sexually discriminatory intimidation." MIMI KO 
</P>
</TEXT>
