<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: LAGUNA BEACH; GROUP TO SEEK CITY SUPPORT FOR FESTIVAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLIE EARNEST 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In a move intended to attract gays and lesbians from surrounding communities 
to visit the city, a local support group is planning the city's first Gay and 
Lesbian Festival. 
</P>
<P>
 Co-sponsor Laguna Outreach is seeking city support for the festival, which 
will include a kick-off party April 29 followed by the weekend event on the 
Festival of Arts grounds. 
</P>
<P>
 Promoters say they hope the two-day celebration will become an annual event. 
</P>
<P>
 The group will not be asking for money at Tuesday's City Council meeting, but 
rather for "moral support," said Laguna Outreach co-chairman Doug Reilly. 
</P>
<P>
 The festival will benefit the city by increasing sales tax revenue. "This is 
one more of a multi-pronged effort to bring people to Laguna Beach," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 A letter from Reilly to the city says the festival "is part of a larger 
(Laguna Outreach) effort to promote Laguna Beach as a resort to the gay and 
lesbian community in Southern California and throughout the nation." 
</P>
<P>
 The City Council commonly endorses community events and Councilman Robert F. 
Gentry is asking his colleagues to support the festival. 
</P>
<P>
 Because the festival is expected to promote business for city restaurants, art 
galleries and hotels, Laguna Outreach will also seek support from the Chamber 
of Commerce. 
</P>
<P>
 The festival will feature a variety of entertainment, including pop and 
country-Western music, dancing and performances by local comedians. 
</P>
<P>
 The memo to the city says money generated by the celebration will be used 
partly to help defray festival expenses and to support a similar event next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
 The remainder would go to Laguna Shanti, an AIDS support group that is 
co-sponsoring the event; Orange County Cultural Pride, which sponsors the 
Lesbian and Gay Pride Festival in August; and Laguna Outreach. 
</P>
<P>
 The Laguna Beach festival is also being co-sponsored by the Coast Inn, home of 
the Boom Boom Room, a gay bar in town. 
</P>
<P>
 The annual Lesbian and Gay Pride Festival has drawn thousands of participants 
in recent years. LESLIE EARNEST 
</P>
</TEXT>
